  "answer": "All four texts address rājadharma (the king's duty), and while they share a common core, each emphasises a different dimension.\n\n**Shared core across all four texts:**\n1. The king was created from essential particles drawn from eight divine beings (Indra, Wind, Yama, Sun, Agni, Varuṇa, Moon, Kubera) — giving the office cosmic authority.\n2. The primary duty is the protection of subjects.\n3. Maintaining the varṇa and āśrama system in their respective dharmas.\n4. Exercising daṇḍa (punishment / the rod of justice) justly.\n5. The king receives a sixth part of the merit generated in his kingdom through proper protection.\n6. Honouring Brāhmaṇas, performing sacrifices, granting gifts.\n\n**Manu** (unknown-manusmrti-347b76, ch. 7) gives the most philosophically elaborate treatment. Rājadharma is inseparable from daṇḍa: 'Daṇḍa rules all subjects, Daṇḍa alone protects them; Daṇḍa is awake when others sleep; the wise know Daṇḍa to be Dharma itself' (Mn_7.18, p-48dedc). Manu frames the king as a cosmic figure — 'through his power, he is Agni and he is the Wind, he is the Sun…' (Mn_7.7) — and stresses self-restraint: the king must conquer the ten vices of desire and eight of anger. The king was 'created as the protector of all the varṇas and āśramas' (Mn_7.35, p-2264d1). Wielding daṇḍa wrongly destroys the king and his kingdom; wielding it rightly brings the three ends of life.\n\n**Yājñavalkya** (unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6, ch. 1, section 13, rājadharmaprakaraṇam, p-065373) is the most systematic. The king should be 'of great energy, generous, grateful, a servant of the aged, disciplined…truthful, and pure' (Yj_1.309, p-179181) and versed in Daṇḍanīti, Ānvīkṣikī (logic), Vārtā (economics), and the three Vedas (Yj_1.311, p-5552ad). The highest formulation: 'There is no higher dharma for kings than that wealth acquired in battle is given to Brāhmaṇas, and that protection is always given to the people' (Yj_1.323, p-c86703). Yājñavalkya gives elaborate treatment of statecraft: the maṇḍala (circle of states) theory (Yj_1.345), the four expedients — conciliation (sāma), gifts (dāna), dissension (bheda), force (daṇḍa), with force as last resort (Yj_1.346, p-20d31d) — and the six political measures. Just punishment is equivalent to sacrifice: the king who punishes the punishable 'is considered to have performed sacrifices with excellent sacrificial fees' (Yj_1.359, p-8ebf08).\n\n**Viṣṇu** (unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8, ch. 3) opens with the most explicit label: 'Now, the duties of a king (rājadharma)' (Vi_3.1, p-6528bf), followed immediately by the most concise two-part definition: 'The protection of the people' (Vi_3.2, p-a023c1) and 'The establishment of the varṇas and āśramas in their respective duties' (Vi_3.3, p-2445ca). Viṣṇu then elaborates a practical administrative code: an administrative hierarchy, specific tax rates (one-sixth of grain annually, two percent from cattle/gold/clothes), exemption of Brāhmaṇas from taxation (Vi_3.26–27), and recovery of stolen property from the royal treasury (Vi_3.67). 'There is no duty for kings equal to giving up one's body in battle' (Vi_3.44, p-0d5c70). The ideal: 'The king who is happy in his subjects' happiness, and who is unhappy in their sorrow…is glorified in heaven after death' (Vi_3.98, p-404192).\n\n**Bṛhaspati** (unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070, ch. 1) focuses rājadharma most specifically on legal procedure and judicial administration. 'In a kingless realm, there is no agriculture, trade, money-lending, or protection; therefore, he was created of old as the leader of the varṇāśrama system' (Brh_1,1.8, p-bf73f8). Protection of subjects is classified threefold: from foreign armies, from thieves, and from powerful unjust men (Brh_1,1.39, p-1a1093). The king receives a sixth of all study, sacrifice, oblation, and worship through proper protection (Brh_1,1.41). Bṛhaspati uses the tree metaphor: 'The Brahmin is the root of the tree of dharma; the king is its trunk and branches; the ministers are the leaves and flowers; the fruit is just protection' (Brh_1,1.49, p-d8a012). By protecting subjects according to dharma and executing those deserving death, 'a king performs sacrifices daily with hundreds of thousands in sacrificial fees' (Brh_1,1.42, p-f29d3d). Bṛhaspati most stresses the judicial role: the king presides over a ten-limbed instrument of justice; just adjudication is the practical heart of rājadharma.\n\n**Summary of differences:** Manu develops rājadharma as a cosmic philosophy of daṇḍa. Yājñavalkya provides the most comprehensive statecraft manual (maṇḍala theory, daily routine, four expedients, six political measures). Viṣṇu gives the most succinct definition (protection of people + maintenance of varṇāśrama) and the most practical administrative code. Bṛhaspati emphasises legal procedure and the king-as-judge as the operational core of rājadharma.",
